# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: link-aggregation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] EtherChannel technology was invented by Kalpana in the early 1990s.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] Kalpana was acquired by Cisco Systems in 1994.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] In 2000, the IEEE passed 802.3ad, which is an open standard version of EtherChannel.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] Using an EtherChannel has numerous advantages, and probably the most desirable aspect is the bandwidth.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] Using the maximum of 8 active ports a total bandwidth of 800 Mbit/s, 8 Gbit/s or 80 Gbit/s is possible depending on port speed.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] This assumes there is a traffic mixture, as those speeds do not apply to a single application only.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] It can be used with Ethernet running on twisted pair wiring, single-mode and multimode fiber.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] Because EtherChannel takes advantage of existing wiring it makes it very scalable.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] It can be used at all levels of the network to create higher bandwidth links as the traffic needs of the network increase.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] All Cisco switches have the ability to support EtherChannel.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] When an EtherChannel is configured all adapters that are part of the channel share the same Layer 2 (MAC) address.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] This makes the EtherChannel transparent to network applications and users because they only see the one logical connection; they have no knowledge of the individual links.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] EtherChannel aggregates the traffic across all the available active ports in the channel.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] The port is selected using a Cisco-proprietary hash algorithm, based on source or destination MAC addresses, IP addresses or TCP and UDP port numbers.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] The hash function gives a number between 0 and 7, and the following table shows how the 8 numbers are distributed among the 2 to 8 physical ports.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] In the hypothesis of real random hash algorithm, 2, 4 or 8 ports configurations lead to fair load-balancing, whereas other configurations lead to unfair load-balancing.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] Fault-tolerance is another key aspect of EtherChannel.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] Should a link fail, the EtherChannel technology will automatically redistribute traffic across the remaining links.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] This automatic recovery takes less than one second and is transparent to network applications and the end user.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] This makes it very resilient and desirable for mission-critical applications.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] Spanning Tree Protocol (STP) can be used with an EtherChannel.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] STP treats all the links as a single one and BPDUs are only sent down one of the links.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] Without the use of an EtherChannel, STP would effectively shutdown any redundant links between switches until one connection goes down.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] This is where an EtherChannel is most desirable, it allows use of all available links between two devices.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] EtherChannels can be also configured as VLAN trunks.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] If any single link of an EtherChannel is configured as a VLAN trunk, the entire EtherChannel will act as a VLAN trunk.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] Cisco ISL, VTP and IEEE 802.1Q are compatible with EtherChannel.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] A limitation of EtherChannel is that all the physical ports in the aggregation group must reside on the same switch except in the case of a switch stack, where they can reside on different switches on the stack.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] Avaya's SMLT protocol removes this limitation by allowing the physical ports to be split between two switches in a triangle configuration or 4 or more switches in a mesh configuration.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] Cisco's Virtual Switching System (VSS) allows the creation of a Multichassis Etherchannel (MEC) similar to the DMLT protocol allowing ports to be aggregated towards different physical chassis that form a single *virtual switch* entity.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] Also Extreme Networks may do this functionality via M-LAG Multilink Agreggation.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] Cisco Nexus series of switches allow the creation of a **Virtual PortChannel** (vPC) between a remote device and two individual Nexus switches.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] The two Cisco Nexus switches involved in a vPC differ from stacking or VSS technology in that stacking and VSS create a single data and control plane across the multiple switches, whereas vPC creates a single data plane across the two Nexus switches while keeping the two control planes separate.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] EtherChannel and IEEE 802.3ad standards are very similar and accomplish the same goal.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] Both technologies are capable of automatically configuring this logical link.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] EtherChannel supports both LACP and Cisco's PAgP, whereas 802.3ad uses LACP.
[src:link-aggregation/etherchannel] LACP allows for up to 8 active and 8 standby links, whereas PAgP only allows for 8 active links.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] The first flow control mechanism, the **pause frame**, was defined by the **IEEE 802.3x** standard.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] A sending station (computer or network switch) may be transmitting data faster than the other end of the link can accept it.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] Using flow control, the receiving station can signal the sender requesting suspension of transmissions until the receiver catches up.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] Flow control on Ethernet can be implemented at the data link layer.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] The first flow control mechanism, the *pause frame*, was defined by the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) task force that defined full duplex Ethernet link segments.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] The IEEE standard 802.3x was issued in 1997.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] An overwhelmed network node can send a pause frame, which halts the transmission of the sender for a specified period of time.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] A media access control (MAC) frame (EtherType 0x8808) is used to carry the pause command, with the Control opcode set to 0x0001 (hexadecimal).
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] Only stations configured for full-duplex operation may send pause frames.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] When a station wishes to pause the other end of a link, it sends a pause frame to either the unique 48-bit destination address of this link or to the 48-bit reserved multicast address of 01-80-C2-00-00-01.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] The use of a well-known address makes it unnecessary for a station to discover and store the address of the station at the other end of the link.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] Another advantage of using this multicast address arises from the use of flow control between network switches.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] The particular multicast address used is selected from a range of addresses that have been reserved by the IEEE 802.1D standard, which specifies the operation of switches used for bridging.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] Normally, a frame with a multicast destination sent to a switch will be forwarded out to all other ports of the switch.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] However, this range of multicast addresses is special and will not be forwarded by an 802.1D-compliant switch.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] Instead, frames sent to this range are understood to be frames meant to be acted upon only within the switch.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] A pause frame includes the period of pause time being requested, in the form of a two-byte (16-bit), unsigned integer (0 through 65535).
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] This number is the requested duration of the pause.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] The pause time is measured in units of pause *quanta*, where each quanta is equal to 512 bit times.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] By 1999, several vendors supported receiving pause frames, but fewer implemented sending them.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] One original motivation for the pause frame was to handle network interface controllers (NICs) that did not have enough buffering to handle full-speed reception.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] This problem has become less common with advances in bus speeds and memory sizes.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] A more likely scenario is network congestion within a switch.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] For example, a flow can come into a switch on a higher speed link than the one it goes out, or several flows can come in over two or more links that total more than an output link's bandwidth.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] These will eventually exhaust any amount of buffering in the switch.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] However, blocking the sending link will cause all flows over that link to be delayed, even those that are not causing any congestion.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] This situation is a case of head-of-line (HOL) blocking, and can happen more often in core network switches due to the large numbers of flows generally being aggregated.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] Many switches use a technique called virtual output queues to eliminate the HOL blocking internally, so they will never send pause frames.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] Another effort began in March 2004, and in May 2004, it became the IEEE P802.3ar Congestion Management Task Force.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] In May 2006, the objectives of the task force were revised to specify a mechanism to limit the transmitted data rate at about 1% granularity.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] The request was withdrawn and the task force was disbanded in 2008.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] Ethernet flow control disturbs the Ethernet class of service (defined in IEEE 802.1p), as the data of all priorities is stopped to clear the existing buffers, which might also consist of low-priority data.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] As a remedy to this problem, Cisco Systems defined its own priority flow control extension to the standard protocol.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] This mechanism uses 14 bytes of the 42-byte padding in a regular pause frame.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] The MAC control opcode for a Priority pause frame is 0x0101.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] Unlike the original pause, Priority pause indicates the pause time in quanta for each of the eight priority classes separately.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] The extension was subsequently standardized by the Priority-based Flow Control (PFC) project authorized on March 27, 2008, as IEEE 802.1Qbb.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] Claudio DeSanti of Cisco was the editor.
[src:link-aggregation/ethernet-flow-control] The effort was part of the data center bridging task group, which developed Fibre Channel over Ethernet.
[src:link-aggregation/frame-networking] A **frame** is a digital data transmission unit in computer networking and telecommunications.
[src:link-aggregation/frame-networking] In packet switched systems, a frame is a simple container for a single network packet.
[src:link-aggregation/frame-networking] In other telecommunications systems, a frame is a repeating structure supporting time-division multiplexing.
[src:link-aggregation/frame-networking] A frame typically includes frame synchronization features consisting of a sequence of bits or symbols that indicate to the receiver the beginning and end of the payload data within the stream of symbols or bits it receives.
[src:link-aggregation/frame-networking] If a receiver is connected to the system during frame transmission, it ignores the data until it detects a new frame synchronization sequence.
[src:link-aggregation/frame-networking] In the OSI model of computer networking, a frame is the protocol data unit at the data link layer.
[src:link-aggregation/frame-networking] Frames are the result of the final layer of encapsulation before the data is transmitted over the physical layer.
[src:link-aggregation/frame-networking] A frame is "the unit of transmission in a link layer protocol, and consists of a link layer header followed by a packet." Each frame is separated from the next by an interframe gap.
[src:link-aggregation/frame-networking] A frame is a series of bits generally composed of frame synchronization bits, the packet payload, and a frame check sequence.
[src:link-aggregation/frame-networking] Examples are Ethernet frames, Wi-Fi frames, 4G frames, Point-to-Point Protocol (PPP) frames, Fibre Channel frames, and V.42 modem frames.
[src:link-aggregation/frame-networking] Often, frames of several different sizes are nested inside each other.
[src:link-aggregation/frame-networking] In telecommunications, specifically in time-division multiplex (TDM) and time-division multiple access (TDMA) variants, a frame is a cyclically repeated data block that consists of a fixed number of time slots, one for each logical TDM channel or TDMA transmitter.
[src:link-aggregation/frame-networking] In this context, a frame is typically an entity at the physical layer.
[src:link-aggregation/frame-networking] TDM application examples are SONET/SDH and the ISDN circuit-switched B-channel, while TDMA examples are Circuit Switched Data used in early cellular voice services.
[src:link-aggregation/frame-networking] The frame is also an entity for time-division duplex, where the mobile terminal may transmit during some time slots and receive during others.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] In computer networking, **link aggregation** is the combining (aggregating) of multiple network connections in parallel by any of several methods.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Link aggregation increases total bandwidth beyond what a single connection could sustain, and provides redundancy where all but one of the physical links may fail without losing connectivity.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] A **link aggregation group** (**LAG**) is the combined collection of physical ports.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Other umbrella terms used to describe the concept include **trunking**, **bundling**, **bonding**, **channeling** or **teaming**.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Implementation may follow vendor-independent standards such as Link Aggregation Control Protocol (LACP) for Ethernet, defined in IEEE 802.1AX or the previous IEEE 802.3ad, but also proprietary protocols.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Link aggregation increases the bandwidth and resilience of Ethernet connections.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Bandwidth requirements do not scale linearly.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Ethernet bandwidths historically have increased tenfold each generation: 10 Mbit/s, 100 Mbit/s, 1000 Mbit/s, 10000 Mbit/s.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] If one started to bump into bandwidth ceilings, then the only option was to move to the next generation, which could be cost prohibitive.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] An alternative solution, introduced by many of the network manufacturers in the early 1990s, is to use link aggregation to combine two physical Ethernet links into one logical link.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Most of these early solutions required manual configuration and identical equipment on both sides of the connection.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] There are three single points of failure inherent to a typical port-cable-port connection, in either a computer-to-switch or a switch-to-switch configuration: the cable itself or either of the ports the cable is plugged into can fail.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Multiple logical connections can be made, but many of the higher level protocols were not designed to fail over completely seamlessly.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Combining multiple physical connections into one logical connection using link aggregation provides more resilient communications.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Network architects can implement aggregation at any of the lowest three layers of the OSI model.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Examples of aggregation at layer 1 (physical layer) include power line (e.g.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] IEEE 802.11) network devices that combine multiple frequency bands.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Ethernet frame in LANs or multi-link PPP in WANs, Ethernet MAC address) aggregation typically occurs across switch ports, which can be either physical ports or virtual ones managed by an operating system.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Aggregation at layer 3 (network layer) in the OSI model can use round-robin scheduling, hash values computed from fields in the packet header, or a combination of these two methods.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Regardless of the layer on which aggregation occurs, it is possible to balance the network load across all links.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] However, in order to avoid out-of-order delivery, not all implementations take advantage of this.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Combining can either occur such that multiple interfaces share one logical address (i.e., IP) or one physical address (i.e., MAC address), or it allows each interface to have its own address.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] The former requires that both ends of a link use the same aggregation method, but has performance advantages over the latter.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] By the mid-1990s, most network switch manufacturers had included aggregation capability as a proprietary extension to increase bandwidth between their switches.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Each manufacturer developed its own method, which led to compatibility problems.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] The IEEE 802.3 working group took up a study group to create an interoperable link layer standard (i.e., encompassing the physical and data-link layers both) in a November 1997 meeting.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] The group quickly agreed to include an automatic configuration feature, which would add in redundancy as well.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] This became known as Link Aggregation Control Protocol (LACP).
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] As of 2000, most gigabit channel-bonding schemes used the IEEE standard of link aggregation, which was formerly clause 43 of the IEEE 802.3 standard added in March 2000 by the IEEE 802.3ad task force.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Nearly every network equipment manufacturer quickly adopted this joint standard over their proprietary standards.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] The 802.3 maintenance task force report for the 9th revision project in November 2006 noted that certain 802.1 layers (such as 802.1X security) were positioned in the protocol stack below link aggregation which was defined as an 802.3 sublayer.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] To resolve this discrepancy, the 802.3ax (802.1AX) task force was formed, resulting in the formal transfer of the protocol to the 802.1 group with the publication of IEEE 802.1AX-2008 on 3 November 2008.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] As of February 2025 the current revision of the standard is 802.1AX-2020.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] For an overview of the history of the 802.1AX standard, see this part of the table on the IEEE 802.1 family of standards.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Within the IEEE Ethernet standards, the Link Aggregation Control Protocol (LACP) provides a method to control the bundling of several physical links together to form a single logical link.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] LACP allows a network device to negotiate an automatic bundling of links by sending LACP packets to its peer, a directly connected device that also implements LACP.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] LACP works by sending frames (LACPDUs) down all links that have the protocol enabled.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] If it finds a device on the other end of a link that also has LACP enabled, that device will independently send frames along the same links in the opposite direction, enabling the two units to detect multiple links between themselves and then combine them into a single logical link.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] LACP can be configured in one of two modes: active or passive.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] In active mode, LACPDUs are sent 1 per second along the configured links.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] In passive mode, LACPDUs are not sent until one is received from the other side, a speak-when-spoken-to protocol.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Most high-end network devices support some form of link aggregation.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Software-based implementations – such as the *BSD *lagg* package, Linux *bonding* driver, Solaris *dladm aggr*, etc. – exist for many operating systems.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] The Linux *bonding* driver provides a method for aggregating multiple network interface controllers (NICs) into a single logical bonded interface of two or more so-called *(NIC) slaves*.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] The majority of modern Linux distributions come with a Linux kernel which has the Linux bonding driver integrated as a loadable kernel module and the *ifenslave* (if = [network] interface) user-level control program pre-installed.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Donald Becker programmed the original Linux bonding driver.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] It came into use with the Beowulf cluster patches for the Linux kernel 2.0.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Modes for the Linux bonding driver (network interface aggregation modes) are supplied as parameters to the kernel bonding module at load time.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] They may be given as command-line arguments to the *insmod* or *modprobe* commands, but are usually specified in a Linux distribution-specific configuration file.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] The behavior of the single logical bonded interface depends upon its specified bonding driver mode.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] in sequential order from the first available NIC slave through the last.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] This mode can cause congestion control issues due to the packet reordering it can introduce.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Only one NIC slave in the bond is active.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] A different slave becomes active if, and only if, the active slave fails.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Transmit network packets based on a hash of the packet's source and destination.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] This selects the same NIC slave for each destination MAC address, IP address, or IP address and port combination, respectively.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] packet delivery and will transmit at the speed of a single NIC.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] This mode provides load balancing and fault tolerance.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Transmit network packets on all slave network interfaces.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Creates aggregation groups that share the same speed and duplex settings.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Utilizes all slave network interfaces in the active aggregator group according to the 802.3ad specification.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] This mode is similar to the XOR mode above and supports the same balancing policies.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] The link is set up dynamically between two LACP-supporting peers.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Linux bonding driver mode that does not require any special network-switch support.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] The outgoing network packet traffic is distributed according to the current load (computed relative to the speed) on each network interface slave.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Incoming traffic is received by one currently designated slave network interface.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] If this receiving slave fails, another slave takes over the MAC address of the failed receiving slave.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] (rlb) for IPv4 traffic and does not require any special network switch support.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] The Linux Team driver provides an alternative to bonding driver.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] The main difference is that Team driver kernel part contains only essential code and the rest of the code (link validation, LACP implementation, decision making, etc.) is run in userspace as a part of *teamd* daemon.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Link aggregation offers an inexpensive way to set up a high-capacity backbone network that transfers multiple times more data than any single port or device can deliver.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Link aggregation also allows the network's backbone speed to grow incrementally as demand on the network increases, without having to replace everything and deploy new hardware.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Most backbone installations install more cabling or fiber optic pairs than is initially necessary.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] This is done because labor costs are higher than the cost of the cable, and running extra cable reduces future labor costs if networking needs change.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Link aggregation can allow the use of these extra cables to increase backbone speeds for little or no extra cost if ports are available.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] When balancing traffic, network administrators often wish to avoid reordering Ethernet frames.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] For example, TCP suffers additional overhead when dealing with out-of-order packets.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] This goal is approximated by sending all frames associated with a particular session across the same link.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Common implementations use L2 or L3 hashes (i.e. based on the MAC or the IP addresses), ensuring that the same flow is always sent via the same physical link.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] However, this may not provide even distribution across the links in the trunk when only a single or very few pairs of hosts communicate with each other, i.e., when the hashes provide too little variation.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] It effectively limits the client bandwidth in aggregate.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] In the extreme, one link is fully loaded while the others are completely idle, and aggregate bandwidth is limited to this single member's maximum bandwidth.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] For this reason, an even load balancing and full utilization of all trunked links is almost never reached in real-life implementations.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] NICs trunked together can also provide network links beyond the throughput of any single NIC.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] For example, this allows a central file server to establish an aggregate 2-gigabit connection using two 1-gigabit NICs teamed together.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Note the data signaling rate will still be 1 Gbit/s, which can be misleading depending on the methodologies used to test throughput after link aggregation is employed.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Microsoft Windows Server 2012 supports link aggregation natively.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Previous Windows Server versions relied on manufacturer support of the feature within their device driver software.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Intel, for example, released Advanced Networking Services (ANS) to bond Intel Fast Ethernet and Gigabit cards.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Nvidia supports teaming with their Nvidia Network Access Manager/Firewall Tool.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] HP has a teaming tool for HP-branded NICs which supports several modes of link aggregation, including 802.3ad with LACP.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] In addition, there is a basic layer-3 aggregation that allows servers with multiple IP interfaces on the same network to perform load balancing, and for home users with more than one internet connection, to increase connection speed by sharing the load on all interfaces.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Broadcom offers advanced functions via Broadcom Advanced Control Suite (BACS), via which the teaming functionality of BASP (Broadcom Advanced Server Program) is available, offering 802.3ad static LAGs, LACP, and *smart teaming* which doesn't require any configuration on the switches to work.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] It is possible to configure teaming with BACS with a mix of NICs from different vendors as long as at least one of them is from Broadcom and the other NICs have the required capabilities to support teaming.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Linux, FreeBSD, NetBSD, OpenBSD, macOS, OpenSolaris and commercial Unix distributions such as AIX implement Ethernet bonding at a higher level and, as long as the NIC is supported by the kernel, can deal with NICs from different manufacturers or using different drivers.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Citrix XenServer and VMware ESX have native support for link aggregation.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] XenServer offers both static LAGs as well as LACP. vSphere 5.1 (ESXi) supports both static LAGs and LACP natively with its virtual distributed switch.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Microsoft's Hyper-V does not offer link aggregation support from the hypervisor level, but the above-mentioned methods for teaming under Windows apply to Hyper-V.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] The modes *active-backup*, *balance-tlb*, and *balance-alb* can also be set up with two or more switches.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] But after failover (like all other modes), in some cases, active sessions may fail (due to ARP problems) and have to be restarted.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] However, almost all vendors have proprietary extensions that resolve some of these issues: they aggregate multiple physical switches into one logical switch.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Nortel's split multi-link trunking (SMLT) protocol allows multiple Ethernet links to be split across multiple switches in a stack, preventing any single point of failure and additionally allowing all switches to be load balanced across multiple aggregation switches from the single access stack.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] These devices synchronize state across an Inter-Switch Trunk (IST) such that they appear to the connecting (access) device to be a single device (switch block) and prevent any packet duplication.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] SMLT provides enhanced resiliency with sub-second failover and sub-second recovery for all speed trunks while operating transparently to end-devices.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Multi-chassis link aggregation group provides similar features in a vendor-nonspecific manner.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] To the connected device, the connection appears as a normal link-aggregated trunk.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] The coordination between the multiple sources involved is handled in a vendor-specific manner.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] In most implementations, all the ports used in an aggregation consist of the same physical type, such as all copper ports (10/100/1000BASE‑T), all multi-mode fiber ports, or all single-mode fiber ports.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] However, all the IEEE standard requires is that each link be full duplex and all of them have an identical speed (10, 100, 1,000 or 10,000 Mbit/s).
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Many switches are PHY independent, meaning that a switch could have a mixture of copper, SX, LX, LX10 or other GBIC/SFP modular transceivers.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] While maintaining the same PHY is the usual approach, it is possible to aggregate a 1000BASE-SX fiber for one link and a 1000BASE-LX (longer, diverse path) for the second link.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] One path may have a longer propagation time, but since most implementations keep a single traffic flow on the same physical link (using a hash of either MAC addresses, IP addresses, or IP/transport-layer port combinations as index) this doesn't cause problematic out-of-order delivery.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] On Ethernet interfaces, channel bonding requires assistance from both the Ethernet switch and the host computer's operating system, which must *stripe* the delivery of frames across the network interfaces in the same manner that I/O is striped across disks in a RAID 0 array.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] For this reason, some discussions of channel bonding also refer to Redundant Array of Inexpensive Nodes (RAIN) or to *redundant array of independent network interfaces*.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] The Point-to-Point Protocol used for dial-up and other connections to the ISP (including DSL) has a standard link aggregation method called Multilink PPP.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Multiple PPP links to the same ISP can be bonded together into a larger-bandwidth link.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] In analog modems, multiple dial-up links over POTS may be bonded.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Throughput over such bonded connections can come closer to the aggregate bandwidth of the bonded links than can throughput under routing schemes that simply load-balance outgoing network connections over the links.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Similarly, multiple DSL lines can be bonded to give higher bandwidth; in the United Kingdom, ADSL is sometimes bonded to give for example 512 kbit/s upload bandwidth and 4 Mbit/s download bandwidth, in areas that only have access to 2 Mbit/s bandwidth.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Under the DOCSIS 3.0 and 3.1 specifications for data over cable TV systems, multiple channels (i.e., radio-frequency ranges in the coax cable) may be bonded.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Under DOCSIS 3.0, up to 32 downstream and 8 upstream channels may be bonded.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] DOCSIS 3.1 defines more complicated arrangements involving aggregation at the level of subcarriers and larger notional channels.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Broadband bonding is a type of channel bonding that refers to the aggregation of multiple channels at OSI layers at level four or above.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Channels bonded can be wired links such as a T-1 or DSL line.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Additionally, it is possible to bond multiple cellular links for an aggregated wireless bonded link.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Other bonding methodologies reside at lower OSI layers, requiring coordination with telecommunications companies for implementation.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Broadband bonding, because it is implemented at higher layers, can be done without this coordination.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] An implementation would include some form of multipath protocol (e.g., multipath TCP) that encapsulates the traffic to a server with higher bandwidth.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] More conventional methods to combine WAN links include load balancing and/or failover at the per-connection (session) level.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] Because existing download managers and other programs already use multiple connections to overcome throttling and overly pessimistic congestion control behavior, balancing connections over different WAN links is sufficient to make use of their bandwidths.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] On IEEE 802.11 (Wi-Fi), channel bonding is used in Super G technology, referred to as 108 Mbit/s.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] It bonds two channels of standard IEEE 802.11g, which has 54 Mbit/s data signaling rate per channel.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] On IEEE 802.11n, a mode with a channel width of 40 MHz is specified.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] This is not channel bonding, but a single channel with double the older 20 MHz channel width, thus using two adjacent 20 MHz bands.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] This allows direct doubling of the PHY data rate from a single 20 MHz channel.
[src:link-aggregation/link-aggregation-control-protocol] IEEE 802.11be (Wi-Fi 7) allows bonding two different bands, Multi-link Operation (MLO).
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] A **network switch** (also called **switching hub**, **bridging hub**, **Ethernet switch**, and—by the IEEE—**MAC bridge**) is networking hardware that connects devices on a computer network by using packet switching to receive and forward data to the destination device.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] A network switch is a multiport network bridge that uses MAC addresses to forward data at the data link layer (layer 2) of the OSI model.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Some switches can also forward data at the network layer (layer 3) by additionally incorporating routing functionality.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Such switches are commonly known as layer-3 switches or multilayer switches.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Switches for Ethernet are the most common form of network switch.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] The first MAC Bridge was invented in 1983 by Mark Kempf, an engineer in the Networking Advanced Development group of Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC).
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] The first two-port bridge product (LANBridge 100) was introduced by that company shortly after.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] The company subsequently produced multi-port switches for both Ethernet and FDDI.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] DEC decided to license its MAC Bridge patent on a royalty-free, non-discriminatory basis that allowed IEEE standardization.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] This permitted a number of other companies to produce multi-port switches, including Kalpana.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Ethernet was initially a shared-access medium, but the introduction of the MAC bridge began its transformation into its most-common point-to-point form without a collision domain.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Switches also exist for other types of networks, including Fibre Channel, Asynchronous Transfer Mode, and InfiniBand.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Unlike repeater hubs, which broadcast the same data out of each port and let the devices pick out the data addressed to them, a network switch learns the Ethernet addresses of connected devices and then only forwards data to the port connected to the device to which it is addressed.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] A switch is a device in a computer network that connects other devices together.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Multiple data cables are plugged into a switch to enable communication between different networked devices.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Switches manage the flow of data across a network by transmitting a received network packet only to the one or more devices for which the packet is intended.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Each networked device connected to a switch can be identified by its network address, allowing the switch to direct the flow of traffic, maximizing the security and efficiency of the network.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] A switch is more intelligent than an Ethernet hub, which simply retransmits packets out of every port of the hub except the port on which the packet was received, unable to distinguish different recipients, and achieves an overall lower network efficiency.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] An Ethernet switch operates at the data link layer (layer 2) of the OSI model to create a separate collision domain for each switch port.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Each device connected to a switch port can transfer data to any of the other ports at any time and the transmissions will not interfere.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Because broadcasts are still being forwarded to all connected devices by the switch, the newly formed network segment continues to be a broadcast domain.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Switches may also operate at higher layers of the OSI model, including the network layer and above.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] A switch that also operates at these higher layers is known as a multilayer switch.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Segmentation involves the use of a switch to split a larger collision domain into smaller ones in order to reduce collision probability and to improve overall network throughput.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] In the extreme case (i.e., micro-segmentation), each device is directly connected to a switch port dedicated to the device.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] In contrast to an Ethernet hub, there is a separate collision domain on each switch port.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] This allows computers to have dedicated bandwidth on point-to-point connections to the network and also to run in full-duplex mode.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Full-duplex mode has only one transmitter and one receiver per collision domain, making collisions impossible.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] The network switch plays an integral role in most modern Ethernet local area networks (LANs).
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Mid-to-large-sized LANs contain a number of linked managed switches.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Small office/home office (SOHO) applications typically use a single switch, or an all-purpose device such as a residential gateway to access small office/home broadband services such as DSL or cable Internet.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] In most of these cases, the end-user device contains a router and components that interface to the particular physical broadband technology.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Many switches have pluggable modules, such as Small Form-factor Pluggable (SFP) modules.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] These modules often contain a transceiver that connects the switch to a physical medium, such as a fiber optic cable.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Alternatively, DAC (Direct Attach Copper) cables may be used in place of modules.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] These modules were preceded by Medium Attachment Units connected via Attachment Unit Interfaces to switches and have evolved over time: the first modules were Gigabit interface converters, followed by XENPAK modules, SFP modules, XFP transceivers, SFP+ modules, QSFP, QSFP-DD, and OSFP modules.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Pluggable modules are also used for transmitting video in broadcast applications.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] CPO is also considerably easier to adapt to water cooling.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Switches are most commonly used as the network connection point for hosts at the edge of a network.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] In the hierarchical internetworking model and similar network architectures, switches are also used deeper in the network to provide connections between the switches at the edge.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] In switches intended for commercial use, built-in or modular interfaces make it possible to connect different types of networks, including Ethernet, Fibre Channel, RapidIO, ATM, ITU-T G.hn and 802.11.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] This connectivity can be at any of the layers mentioned.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] While the layer-2 functionality is adequate for bandwidth-shifting within one technology, interconnecting technologies such as Ethernet and Token Ring is performed more easily at layer 3 or via routing.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Devices that interconnect at the layer 3 are traditionally called routers.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Where there is a need for a great deal of analysis of network performance and security, switches may be connected between WAN routers as places for analytic modules.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Some vendors provide firewall, network intrusion detection, and performance analysis modules that can plug into switch ports.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Some of these functions may be on combined modules.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Through port mirroring, a switch can create a mirror image of data that can go to an external device, such as intrusion detection systems and packet sniffers.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] A modern switch may implement power over Ethernet (PoE), which avoids the need for attached devices, such as a VoIP phone or wireless access point, to have a separate power supply.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Because switches can have their power circuits connected to uninterruptible power supplies, the connected device can continue operating even when regular office power fails.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] In 1989 and 1990, Kalpana introduced the first multiport Ethernet switch, its seven-port EtherSwitch.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Modern commercial switches primarily use Ethernet interfaces.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] The core function of an Ethernet switch is to provide multiple ports of layer-2 bridging.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Layer-1 functionality is required in all switches in support of the higher layers.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Many switches also perform operations at other layers.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] A device capable of more than bridging is known as a multilayer switch.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] A layer 2 network device is a multiport device that uses hardware addresses (MAC addresses) to process and forward data at the data link layer (layer 2).
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] A switch operating as a network bridge may interconnect otherwise separate layer 2 networks.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] The bridge learns the MAC address of each connected device, storing this data in a table that maps MAC addresses to ports.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] This table is often implemented using high-speed content-addressable memory (CAM), some vendors refer to the MAC address table as a CAM table.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Bridges also buffer an incoming packet and adapt the transmission speed to that of the outgoing port.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] While there are specialized applications, such as storage area networks, where the input and output interfaces are the same bandwidth, this is not always the case in general LAN applications.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] In LANs, a switch used for end-user access typically concentrates lower bandwidth and uplinks into a higher bandwidth.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] The Ethernet header at the start of the frame contains all the information required to make a forwarding decision; some high-performance switches can begin forwarding the frame to the destination whilst still receiving the frame payload from the sender.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] This cut-through switching can significantly reduce latency through the switch.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Interconnects between switches may be regulated using the Spanning Tree Protocol (STP) that disables forwarding on links so that the resulting local area network is a tree without switching loops.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] In contrast to routers, spanning tree bridges must have topologies with only one active path between two points.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Shortest path bridging and TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links) are layer 2 alternatives to STP, which allow all paths to be active with multiple equal cost paths.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Rack-mounted switches may be stand-alone units, stackable switches or large chassis units with swappable line cards.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] It is difficult to monitor traffic that is bridged using a switch because only the sending and receiving ports can see the traffic.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] These monitoring features are rarely present on consumer-grade switches.
[src:link-aggregation/network-switch] Other monitoring methods include connecting a layer-1 hub or network tap between the monitored device and its switch port.
